dy-all\n}}</ref>\n|source 2 = Ogimet (sun 1981\u20132010)<ref name=ogimet>{{cite web\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200331154243/https://www.ogimet.com/cgi-bin/gclimat?lang=en&mode=0&ind=85682&ord=DIR&year=2019&mes=12&months=12\n| archivedate = 31 March 2020\n| url = https://www.ogimet.com/cgi-bin/gclimat?lang=en&mode=0&ind=85682&ord=DIR&year=2019&mes=12&months=12\n| title = CLIMAT summary for 85682: Concepcion (Chile) \u2013 Section 2: Monthly Normals\n| work = CLIMAT monthly weather summaries\n| publisher = Ogimet\n| accessdate = 31 March 2020\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref>\n|date      = December 2013}}\n\nAs might be expected for such a large urban area heavily dependent on wood-burning for heat and diesel for transport, the air in Concepci\u00f3n is the third-most polluted in Chile, after [[Santiago]] and [[Temuco]].<ref>[http://en.mercopress.com/2007/06/29/severe-air-pollution-plagues-chilean-cities Severe air pollution plagues Chilean cities] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525232346/http://en.mercopress.com/2007/06/29/severe-air-pollution-plagues-chilean-cities |date=2014-05-25 }} Friday, June 29th 2007 \u2013 21:00 UTC</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{historical populations\n|percentages = pagr\n|1970 |161,006 \n|1982 |267,891 \n|1992 |326,784 \n|2002 |216,061\n|2006 |225,158 \n|2012 |229,684 \n|source = 1970\u20131992,<ref name=\"cenanti\">According to [https://web.archive.org/web/20070320040225/http://www.censo2002.cl/menu_superior/ultimos/index.htm Last 5 census], the [[National Institute of Statistics (Chile)|INE]]</ref> 2002,<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">According to Census 2002, operated by the [[National Institute of Statistics (Chile)|INE]]. Note that the agency's projections indicate that 2006 the estimated population of 225,158 inhabitants.</ref> 2006\u20132012<ref name=autogenerated1>Projections by the [[National Institute of Statistics (Chile)|INE]].</ref>\n}}\n\nAccording to data collected on 2002 in the Census of the [[National Institute of Statistics (Chile)|National Institute of Statistics]], the township has an area of {{convert|221.6|sqkm|0|abbr=on}} and a population of 216,061 inhabitants, of whom 103,860 are men and 112,201 are women.\n\nConception is home to 11.61% of the total population of the region. 1.88% (4,058 persons) is for rural population and 98.12% (212,003) to urban population.\n\nBetween 1970 and 1982 there is a large increase in the population. One reason is the inclusion of [[San Pedro de la Paz|San Pedro]], segregated from the municipality of [[Coronel, Chile|Coronel]].\n\nThe Concepci\u00f3n commune population declined sharply because in 1996 it was divided, creating [[Chiguayante]] and [[San Pedro de la Paz]]. In these communes the population has grown quickly since they have become [[bedroom communities]] of ''Concepci\u00f3n'', i.e. residential cities that do not have a center with many shops, such as Concepcion.\n\nIt is projected that by 2009 an estimated population of 227,768 inhabitants live in the commune.<ref name=\"proyec\"/>\n\nThere is a significant percentage of foreign residents in the city, the most numerous are the [[Spain|Spanish]], [[Italy|Italian]] and [[United States|US]] expatriate communities. There are also smaller segments of [[German people|German]], [[French people|French]], [[British people|British]], [[Dutch people|Dutch]], [[Greek people|Greek]], [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]], [[Croats|Croatian]], [[Scandinavia]]n, [[Arab]] and [[Australian]] descendants in a city settled by waves of immigration.\n\n==Cultural life==\n[[File:A\u00f1o nuevo en Concepci\u00f3n.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Fireworks in celebration for the arrival of 2007 in Concepci\u00f3n]]\nTo an outsider, there may be confusion between the [[demonym]]s of the inhabitants of Concepci\u00f3n and the nearby city of Penco. Due to the previous location of Concepci\u00f3n being where Penco currently stands, inhabitants of Concepci\u00f3n are called ''penquistas'' while inhabitants of Penco are known as ''pencones''.\n\nConcepci\u00f3n is one of the most active cities in Chilean rock music and many rock groups in Chile were formed in Concepci\u00f3n. The city has the second largest concentration of universities in Chile, and is home to [[Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n]], [[Universidad Cat\u00f3lica de la Sant\u00edsima Concepci\u00f3n]], [[Universidad T\u00e9cnica Federico Santa Mar\u00eda]] and  [[Universidad del B\u00edo B\u00edo]]\n[[File:Lostres.jpg|thumb|200px|The [[Los Tres]] band was born in the city of Concepci\u00f3n]]\n\n===Music===\nConcepci\u00f3n has been described as the \"capital of Chilean rock\",{{fact|date=November 2019}} since numerous bands of this [[Rock music|genre]] have been founded in the city, such as [[Los Tres]], [[Los Bunkers]], [[Emociones Clandestinas]] and [[Santos Dumont (band)|Santos Dumont]]. Numerous bands have played their first major concerts in the city, such as [[Los Prisioneros]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Nuestro.cl |title=El sorprendente sonido penquista |url=http://www.nuestro.cl/notas/rescate/sonido_penquista1.htm |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |accessdate=20 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204154854/http://www.nuestro.cl/notas/rescate/sonido_penquista1.htm |archivedate=4 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\nConcepci\u00f3n is also known{{bywho|date=November 2019}} as \"the university city\",{{fact|date=November 2019}} for the number of universities that exist and which also represent an alternative to various regions of Chile.\n\n==Sports==\nConcepci\u00f3n is home of three professional [[Association football|football]] teams:\n* [[Club Deportivo Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n]], currently in the [[Chilean Primera Divisi\u00f3n|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]]\n* [[Club Deportivo Ferroviario Almirante Arturo Fern\u00e1ndez Vial]], currently in the Chilean second division\n* [[Club de Deportes Concepci\u00f3n]], currently in the Chilean third division.\n\n[[Basketball]] is also played at a high professional level. The most notable team is:\n*Club Deportivo Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n, currently in DIMAYOR, [[Divisi\u00f3n Mayor del B\u00e1squetbol de Chile]]\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Mercado Central de Concepci\u00f3n.jpg|thumb|Concepci\u00f3n is the second commercial nucleus of [[Chile]]. In the image, the Concepci\u00f3n Central Market]]\n\nHistorically characterized by a strong manufacturing industry, Concepci\u00f3n has also been a major center for distribution and services and the financial basis of the regional economy.\n\n===Commerce===\nTrade in the city is concentrated in the ''Plaza Independencia'' (Independence Square), the pedestrian street ''Alonso de Ercilla y Z\u00fa\u00f1iga'' (built in 1981), and along the major avenues. One such avenue is the ''Diego Barros Arana''  street which has developed into the commercial center of the city and the region was until 1907 even known as \"''calle Comercio''\" (\"Commerce Street\"). New commercial centers are being developed around the old central station and the new civic district as a part of the Chilean bicentennial (September 18, 2010). A considerable percentage of local trade is taking place in settlements around the city, in communes such as [[Hualp\u00e9n]], [[Talcahuano]] and [[San Pedro de la Paz]], where there are bustling shopping centers, such as [[Mall Plaza del Tr\u00e9bol]], and where there is a constant commercial development.\n\nOther commercial spots, related to food, are the [[Vega Monumental]] and [[Central market of Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Mercado Central de Concepci\u00f3n]] (Central Market of Concepci\u00f3n) places offering various services and agricultural and livestock products.\n\n==Administration==\nAs a [[Communes of Chile|commune]], Concepci\u00f3n is a third-level [[administrative division of Chile]] administered by a [[municipal council]], headed by an [[alcalde]] who is directly elected every four years. The 2016\u20132020 mayor is Alvaro Ortiz Vera ([[Christian Democratic Party (Chile)|Christian Democratic Party]]), who was first elected in 2012. The communal council has 10 seats, which are currently occupied (2016\u20132020) by three for [[Christian Democratic Party (Chile)|Christian Democratic Party]], two for [[National Renewal (Chile)|National Renewal]], two for [[Independent Democrat Union]], one for [[Communist Party of Chile|Communist Party]], one for [[Socialist Party of Chile|Socialist Party]], and one for [[Social Democrat Radical Party|Radical Party]]. The following members are:<ref name=\"Official\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Seats !! Councillor !! Party\n|-\n|1 || Fabiola Troncoso Alvarado || bgcolor={{Christian Democratic Party (Chile)/meta/color}}| Christian Democratic\n|-\n|2 || Yanina Contreras \u00c1lvarez || bgcolor={{National Renewal (Chile)/meta/color}} style=\"color:#FFFFFF;\"| National Renewal\n|-\n|3 || Jaime Monjes Farias || bgcolor={{Christian Democratic Party (Chile)/meta/color}}| Christian Democratic\n|-\n|4 || Emilio Armstrong Delpin || bgcolor={{Independent Democratic Union/meta/color}} style=\"color:#FFFFFF;\"|I.D.U.\n|-\n|5 || Christian Paulsen Espejo-Pando || bgcolor={{Independent Democratic Union/meta/color}} style=\"color:#FFFFFF;\"|I.D.U.\n|-\n|6 || Joaquin Eguiluz Herrera || bgcolor={{National Renewal (Chile)/meta/color}} style=\"color:#FFFFFF;\"| National Renewal\n|-\n|7 || Alex Iturra Jara || bgcolor={{Communist Party of Chile/meta/color}} style=\"color:#FFFFFF;\"| Communist\n|-\n|8 || Boris Negrete Canales || bgcolor={{Christian Democratic Party (Chile)/meta/color}}| Christian Democratic\n|-\n|9 || Patricia Garcia Mora || bgcolor={{Socialist Party of Chile/meta/color}}| Socialist\n|-\n|10 || Ricardo Trostel Provoste || bgcolor={{Social Democratic Radical Party/meta/color}}| Radical\n|}\n\nWithin the [[electoral divisions of Chile]], Concepci\u00f3n is represented in the [[Chamber of Deputies of Chile|Chamber of Deputies]] by Gaston Saavedra ([[Socialist Party of Chile|PS]]), Jos\u00e9 Miguel Ortiz ([[Christian Democratic Party|PDC]]), Jaime Toha (PS), Felix Gonzalez ([[Green Ecologist Party (Chile)|PEV]]), Enrique Van Rysselberghe (UDI), Sergio Bobadilla (UDI), Francesca Mu\u00f1oz (RN) and Leonidas Romero (RN), as part of the 21st electoral district ([[Concepci\u00f3n Province, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n Province]] without [[Lota, Chile|Lota]]). The commune is represented in the [[Senate of Chile|Senate]] by Alejandro Navarro Brain ([[Broad Social Movement|MAS]]) and Jacqueline Van Rysselberghe (UDI) as part of the 12th senatorial constituency (Biob\u00edo-Costa).\n\n==Notable citizens==\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Joaqu\u00edn Prieto]] \u2013 [[President of Chile]] between 1831 and 1841.\n*[[Manuel Bulnes]] \u2013 President of Chile between 1841 and 1851.\n*[[Enrique Molina Garmendia]] \u2013 Founder of the University of Concepci\u00f3n, one of the top universities in Chile.\n*[[Luis Altamirano]] \u2013 President of the [[Government Junta of Chile (1924)|1924 Government Junta of Chile]]\n*[[Graciela Araya]] \u2013 opera singer\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda de la Cruz]] \u2013 Soldier\n*[[Adri\u00e1n Garc\u00eda]] \u2013 Tennis player\n*[[Lisando Henr\u00edquez]] \u2013 Footballer\n*[[Ignacio Urrutia Manzano]] \u2013 Politician\n*[[Adelqui Migliar]] \u2013 Film actor, director, writer and producer\n*[[Jos\u00e9 A. Santos]] \u2013 Retired American jockey\n*[[Paulina Veloso]] \u2013 Lawyer and [[Socialist Party of Chile|Socialist Party]] politician\n*[[An\u00edbal Za\u00f1artu]] \u2013 Politician\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\nThe following cities have [[Twin towns and sister cities|sister city associations]] with Concepci\u00f3n.\n* [[Cascavel]], [[Brazil]]\n* [[Bethlehem]], [[Palestinian National Authority]]\n* [[Guayaquil]], [[Ecuador]]\n* [[Rosario, Santa Fe|Rosario]], [[Argentina]]\n* [[La Plata]], [[Argentina]]\n* [[Auckland City|Auckland]], [[New Zealand]]\n* [[Sucre]], [[Bolivia]]\n* [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]]\n* [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]]\n* [[Nanjing]], [[China]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Greater Concepci\u00f3n]]\n* [[Santa Juana, Chile|Santa Juana]]\n* [[Florida, Chile|Florida]]\n* [[Dichato]]\n* [[Lirqu\u00e9n, Chile|Lirqu\u00e9n]]\n* [[Biob\u00edo River]]\n* [[History of the territorial organization of Chile]]\n\n==References==\n* Ida Stevenson Weldon Vernon (1969) ''Pedro de Valdivia, Conquistador of Chile'', Greenwood Press\n* John Milton Nickles, Marie Siegrist (1965) ''Bibliography and Index of Geology Exclusive of North America'', Geological Society of America, v.28\n\n===Line notes===\n{{Reflist|group=FN}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n}}\n{{Wiktionary|Concepci\u00f3n}}\n*[[El Sur (newspaper)|El Sur]] [https://web.archive.org/web/19981202055452/http://www.elsur.cl/ ''El Sur'', newspaper of Concepci\u00f3n] {{in lang|es}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20141218153635/http://viveconce.cl/ ''Viveconce'', Event schedule of Concepci\u00f3n] {{in lang|es}}\n* [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/130916/Concepcion Source about Concepci\u00f3n \u2013 Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]\n* [http://www.fallingrain.com/world/CI/06/Concepcion.html Geographical coordinates and NASA images, Google] \n*{{Wikivoyage-inline|Concepci\u00f3n}}\n\n{{Concepcion}}\n{{Communes in B\u00edo B\u00edo Region}}\n{{Large cities of Chile}}\n{{2010 Chile earthquake}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Concepcion, Chile}}\n[[Category:Concepci\u00f3n, Chile| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Communes of Chile]]\n[[Category:Capitals of Chilean regions]]\n[[Category:Capitals of Chilean provinces]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1550]]\n[[Category:Geography of Biob\u00edo Region]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Concepci\u00f3n Province]]\n[[Category:1550 establishments in the Spanish Empire]]\n[[Category:1550 establishments in South America]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=September 2010}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Concepci\u00f3n\n| other_name                      = La Concepci\u00f3n de Mar\u00eda Pur\u00edsima<br/>del Nuevo Extremo (original name)\n| settlement_type                 = [[List of cities in Chile|City]] and [[Communes of Chile|Commune]]\n| image_skyline                   = Ciudad-Puerto-de-Concepci\u00f3n.png\n| imagesize                       = 300px\n| image_caption                   = Collage from Concepci\u00f3n, Top: Skyline; Upper left: University of Concepci\u00f3n; Upper right: Store in downtown; Middle left: Ecuador Park; Middle center: Bonilla/Alonso de Ribera Highway; Middle right: University of Concepci\u00f3n clock tower; Lower left: Lautaro statue; Lower center: San Sebasti\u00e1n University; Bottom center: Court of Appeals; Bottom right: Biotr\u00e9n.\n| image_flag                      = Flag of Concepcion, Chile.svg\n| flag_size                       = 130px\n| flag_alt                        = Flag of Concepcion\n| seal_size                       = 70px\n| seal_alt                        = Coat of arms\n| image_shield                    = Coat of arms of Concepcion, Chile.svg\n| nicknames                       = Biob\u00edo's Pearl, The University City, The cradle of Chilean rock\n| motto                           = ''La Capital del Sur de Chile''<br/>The Capital of Southern Chile\n| image_map                       = Txu-oclc-224571178-sj18-04.jpg\n| map_alt                         = Location in the B\u00edo B\u00edo Region\n| map_caption                     = Location in the B\u00edo B\u00edo Region\n| pushpin_map_narrow              = yes\n| pushpin_map                     = Chile\n| pushpin_label_position          = bottom\n| pushpin_map_alt                 = Location in Chile\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Chile\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|36|49|41.50|S|73|03|04.93|W|region:CL-BI|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint                   = Alcalde's office\n| coordinates_footnotes           = \n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = [[Chile]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Regions of Chile|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[B\u00edo B\u00edo Region|B\u00edo B\u00edo]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Provinces of Chile|Province]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Concepci\u00f3n Province, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]]\n| established_title               = Founded\n| established_date                = October 5, 1550\n| founder                         = [[Pedro de Valdivia]]\n| government_type                 = [[Municipality]]\n| government_footnotes            = <ref name=\"Official\">{{cite web|url=http://www.concepcion.cl/|title=Municipality of Concepci\u00f3n|accessdate=3 September 2010|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211124604/http://www.concepcion.cl/|archive-date=11 February 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| leader_party                    = [[Christian Democratic Party (Chile)|DC]]\n| leader_title                    = [[Alcalde]]\n| leader_name                     = \u00c1lvaro Ortiz\n| area_total_km2                  = 222\n| area_metro_footnotes            = City proper\n| elevation_m                     = 12\n| population_total                = 992,589\n| population_as_of                = 2006\n| population_density_km2          = 1318\n| population_metro                = 1,322,581\n| population_demonym              = Penquista\n| timezone                        = [[Time in Chile|CLT]]\n| utc_offset                      = \u22124\n| timezone_DST                    = [[Time in Chile|CLST]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = \u22123\n| postal_code_type                = Post code\n| postal_code                     = 3349001\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone prefix\n| area_code                       = 56 + 41\n| blank_name                      = [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|Climate]]\n| blank_info                      = [[Warm-summer mediterranean climate|Csb]]\n| website                         = {{url|www.concepcion.cl/}} {{in lang|es}}\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n'''Concepci\u00f3n''' ({{IPA-es|kon.sep\u02c8sjon|-|Es-Concepci\u00f3n.ogg}}; in full: ''Concepci\u00f3n de la Madre Sant\u00edsima de la Luz'', \"Conception of the Blessed Mother of Light\") is a city in central [[Chile]] and the core of the [[Communes of Chile|commune]] and [[metropolitan area]] of [[Greater Concepci\u00f3n]], the country's second largest urban conurbation.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.scielo.cl/scielo.php?script=sci_abstract&pid=S0250-71612009000200003&lng=es&nrm=iso&tlng=es|title=Estructura urbana y policentrismo en el \u00c1rea Metropolitana de Concepci\u00f3n|first1=Rojas|last1=Quezada|first2=Carolina|last2=Alejandra|first3=Iv\u00e1n|last3=Mu\u00f1iz Olivera|first4=Miguel \u00c1ngel|last4=Garc\u00eda-L\u00f3pez|date=1 August 2009|publisher=|volume=35|issue=105|pages=47\u201370|via=SciELO|doi=10.4067/S0250-71612009000200003|journal=|access-date=31 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112021509/http://www.scielo.cl/scielo.php?script=sci_abstract&pid=S0250-71612009000200003&lng=es&nrm=iso&tlng=es|archive-date=12 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It has a significant impact on domestic trade<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soychile.cl/Concepcion/Economia-y-Negocios/2011/04/15/8751/Concepcion-la-nueva-capital-de-negocios-del-sur-de-Chile.aspx|title=Concepci\u00f3n: la nueva capital de negocios del sur de Chile \u2013 soyconcepcion.cl|author=|date=|website=soychile.cl|access-date=2013-01-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203014545/http://www.soychile.cl/Concepcion/Economia-y-Negocios/2011/04/15/8751/Concepcion-la-nueva-capital-de-negocios-del-sur-de-Chile.aspx|archive-date=2013-12-03|url-status=live}}</ref> being part of the most heavily industrialized region in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ine.cl/canales/chile_estadistico/territorio/publicaciones/pdf/crecimiento_y_disparidad_regionales.pdf|title=INE \u2013 Error 404|author=|date=|website=www.ine.cl|access-date=2013-01-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126155101/http://www.ine.cl/canales/chile_estadistico/territorio/publicaciones/pdf/crecimiento_y_disparidad_regionales.pdf|archive-date=2013-01-26|url-status=live}}</ref> Its location is in the called ''[[Chilean Central Valley|Zona Centro]] [[Zona Sur|Sur]]'' (Central South Zone), in the geographic center of the country,<ref>{{cite web |author=Coronel.cl |title=Hito Centro Geogr\u00e1fico de Chile Continental |url=http://www.coronel.cl/2011/06/hito-centro-geografico-de-chile-continental/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215211913/http://www.coronel.cl/2011/06/hito-centro-geografico-de-chile-continental/ |archivedate=2013-12-15 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |accessdate=20 January 2013 |quote=[[Playa Blanca]] (comuna de [[Coronel (Chile)|Coronel]], corresponde a la representaci\u00f3n del Centro Geogr\u00e1fico de Chile Continental. El Hito corresponde a una estructura monol\u00edtica de hormig\u00f3n de tan solo 2,5 metros de altura, y posee una forma de flecha que indica la orientaci\u00f3n Norte-[[Arica]] y Sur-[[Punta Arenas]]. }}</ref> and it is the capital of the [[Concepci\u00f3n Province, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n Province]] and [[B\u00edo B\u00edo Region]]. It sits about 500&nbsp;km south of [[Santiago]], the country's capital.\n\n[[Greater Concepci\u00f3n]] (''Gran Concepci\u00f3n'', including [[Talcahuano]], [[San Pedro de la Paz]], [[Hualp\u00e9n]], [[Chiguayante]], [[Penco]], [[Tom\u00e9]], [[Lota, Chile|Lota]], [[Coronel, Chile|Coronel]], [[Hualqui]] and Concepci\u00f3n) is the second-largest [[conurbation]] in the country, with 945,650 inhabitants (2012 census). Individually, it is the 11th largest [[Communes of Chile|commune]] in the country, with a population of 229,665.<ref name=proyec>Seg\u00fan proyecciones del [[Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edsticas de Chile|INE]].</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Plaza de la Independencia (1910).jpg|thumb|left|Plaza de la Independencia, the Plaza de Armas of Concepci\u00f3n, in 1910]]\n[[File:Concepci\u00f3n (Chile).jpg|left|thumb|220x220px|Skyline]]\nConcepci\u00f3n was founded by Don [[Pedro de Valdivia]]<ref group=FN>I.S.W. Vernon, 1969</ref> in 1550 north of the [[B\u00edo B\u00edo River]], at the site which is today known as [[Penco]]. At that time it was given the name ''Concepci\u00f3n de Mar\u00eda Pur\u00edsima del Nuevo Extremo'' (Mary Immaculate Conception of the New End). The new settlement of Concepci\u00f3n was just a few kilometers north of ''[[La Frontera (geographical region)|La Frontera]]'' (The Frontier), the boundary between [[Spain|Spanish]] territory and the land of the [[Mapuche]], an American Indian ethnic group that remained independent until the 1870s. The settlement was formally recognized by the Spanish authorities as a town two years later by a royal decree. It was given a coat-of-arms that is still in use today.\n\nAt the time of the Spanish arrival to the Concepci\u00f3n area chronicler [[Jer\u00f3nimo de Vivar]] noted local Mapuches wore gold and silver [[bracelet]]s and \"sort of crowns\". This is interpreted either as [[Incas in Central Chile|Incan]] gifts, war spoils from defeated Incas, or adoption of Incan [[metallurgy]].<ref name=Silva1983>{{cite journal |last1=Silva Galdames |first1=Osvaldo |date=1983 |title=\u00bfDetuvo la batalla del Maule la expansi\u00f3n inca hacia el sur de Chile? |url=https://revistas.uchile.cl/index.php/CDH/article/download/46464/48492 |journal=Cuadernos de Historia |language=Spanish |volume=3 |issue= |pages=7\u201325 |doi= |access-date=January 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013520/https://revistas.uchile.cl/index.php/CDH/article/download/46464/48492 |archive-date=February 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAlthough Concepci\u00f3n was a significant military settlement for the [[Captaincy General of Chile]], it was overrun and destroyed by [[Arauco War|Mapuche armies]] in 1554, and once again after being refounded in 1555. Concepci\u00f3n was restored during the governorship of [[Garc\u00eda Hurtado de Mendoza, 5th Marquis of Ca\u00f1ete|Garc\u00eda Hurtado de Mendoza]] when he landed there and built a fort on the Alto de Pinto in 1557. The town was refounded once more on January 6, 1558, by captain Jer\u00f3nimo de Villegas. It became the headquarters of the military forces engaged against the [[Mapuche]] in [[Araucan\u00eda (historic region)|La Araucan\u00eda]] over the next two centuries, growing to a population of 10,000 despite a [[siege]] in 1564 and other attacks by the Mapuche. Concepci\u00f3n was the home of the [[Audiencia Real|Real Audiencia]] from 1565 to 1575.\n\n[[Earthquakes]] and [[tsunamis]], which razed the town in [[1570 Concepci\u00f3n earthquake|1570]], 1657, 1687, 1730 and [[1751 Concepci\u00f3n earthquake|1751]], led the authorities to move the town to its current site in the [[Valle de la Mocha]], alongside the [[B\u00edo B\u00edo River]]; the old site lay empty until March 29, 1842, when the present town of [[Penco]] was founded.\n\nThe new site for the town of Concepci\u00f3n became the main town of the Intendancy of Concepci\u00f3n, whose jurisdiction extended from the [[Maule River]] to La Frontera. The first Intendant of Concepci\u00f3n was the Irishman [[Ambrose O'Higgins, Marquis of Osorno]], who later became [[Royal Governor of Chile]] and [[List of Viceroys of Peru|Viceroy of Peru]].\n\nWhen the First National Government Board met in [[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]] on September 18, 1810, citizens of Concepci\u00f3n joined up. Concepci\u00f3n was used as the point of entry by the Spanish Army in the attempt by the [[Viceroyalty of Peru]] to re-conquer Chile. Concepci\u00f3n politicians and soldiers became a significant political force in the newly independent country.\n\nOn January 1, 1818, Ambrose O'Higgins's son, [[Bernardo O'Higgins]], proclaimed and took the oath of the [[Chilean War of Independence]] in the main square of Concepci\u00f3n, which since then has been known as \"Plaza de la Independencia\". On February 20, 1835, the town again was largely destroyed by [[1835 Concepci\u00f3n earthquake|an earthquake]] and had to be rebuilt.\n\nBy 1875, a key British community and German colony existed within the province.  By 1895, there was an even larger Spanish presence.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Edmundson |first1=William |title=A History of the British Presence in Chile: From Bloody Mary to Charles Darwin and the Decline of British Influence |date=2009 |publisher=Palgrave MacMillan |location=New York |isbn=9780230114838 |pages=126}}</ref>\n\nConcepci\u00f3n is the second largest city of Chile. The [[Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n]], founded in 1919, became the first secular private university in Chile. The neighboring harbor of Talcahuano is the site of the largest naval base in Chile.\n\n[[File:Torre O\u00b4Higgins conce.jpg|thumb|left|The partially collapsed O'Higgins Tower]]\n\nOn February 27, 2010, an [[2010 Chile earthquake|8.8 magnitude earthquake]] struck the city of Concepci\u00f3n, killing more than 521 people and injuring thousands nationwide. Following the earthquake, geologists relying on global positioning satellite (GPS) data concluded that the city had been displaced roughly {{convert|3|m|ft|abbr=off|sp=us}} to the west as a result of the event.<ref>CNN, [http://www.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/americas/03/09/chile.earth.shifts/index.html?hpt=T2 \"Chile quake moves city more than 10 feet\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312141611/http://www.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/americas/03/09/chile.earth.shifts/index.html?hpt=T2 |date=2010-03-12 }}, \"9 March 2010\" (accessed 10 March 2010)</ref> The tsunami that followed missed the city.<ref>Time Magazine, [http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1969570,00.html \"Quake Response Doesn't Live Up to Chile's Self-Image\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100306092346/http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1969570,00.html |date=2010-03-06 }}, '''Eben Harrell''', ''4 March 2010'' (accessed 4 March 2010)</ref>\n\nAfter the [[2010 Chile earthquake]], a [[prison riot]] began in Concepci\u00f3n's [[El Manzano (prison)|El Manzano]] prison following a failed escape attempt by the inmates. Different parts of the prison were set on fire and the riot was controlled only after the guards shot into the air and received help from military units.<ref>[[El Mercurio]], March 1. Cuerpo C, page C13</ref> As of 5 March 2010, a Peruvian field hospital has been deployed to the city.<ref name=UKPA-2010-03-06>UKPA, [https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5iBff_XdP-pA7r-utFKQZ9iV3hxiA \"Foreign hospitals help out Chile\"]{{dead link|date=October 2016}}, ''6 March 2010'' (accessed 6 March 2010)</ref>\n\n==Seismology==\nLike most of Chilean territory, the Concepci\u00f3n region is [[Seismology|seismically active]], with much of Concepci\u00f3n destroyed by a violent [[1939 Chill\u00e1n earthquake|earthquake in 1939]]. An [[1953 Concepci\u00f3n earthquake|earthquake in 1953]] damaged 15% of the town's buildings. Another major [[1960 Concepci\u00f3n earthquake|earthquake in 1960]] had a nearby epicenter.<ref group=FN>J.M. Nickles, 1965</ref>\n\nOn February 27, 2010, [[2010 Chile earthquake|an earthquake]] of 8.8 magnitude struck at 35.846\u00b0S, 72.719\u00b0W, {{convert|115|km|mi|abbr=on}} NNE of the city. The United States Geological Survey said the earthquake struck at 0334 GMT on Saturday at a depth of {{convert|35|km|mi|abbr=on}}. The effects were felt as far away as [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Brazil]]\u2014{{convert|2870|mi|km}}.\n\n==Education==\nConcepci\u00f3n is known as ''\"the university city\"''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bblatinamerica.com/es/chile/20-biobio/56-concepcion.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019014107/http://www.bblatinamerica.com/es/chile/20-biobio/56-concepcion.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-10-19|title=Concepci\u00f3n|work=bblatinamerica.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.welcomechile.com/concepcion/|title=Turismo en Concepci\u00f3n 2017: Vacaciones de verano en Concepci\u00f3n|author=|date=|work=welcomechile.com|access-date=2013-01-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130203114648/http://www.welcomechile.com/concepcion/|archive-date=2013-02-03|url-status=live}}</ref> thanks to the numerous universities within the urban agglomeration,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://servicios.universia.cl/contenidos/mapas/|title=MAPA GEOGRAFICO DE LAS UNIVERSIDADES SOCIAS DE UNIVERSIA|last=www.universia.cl|work=universia.cl|access-date=2013-01-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204094950/http://servicios.universia.cl/contenidos/mapas/|archive-date=2013-12-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> since one of the most important universities of the country were founded here, such as the [[Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n]], [[Universidad Cat\u00f3lica de la Sant\u00edsima Concepci\u00f3n]] and [[Universidad del Biob\u00edo]]. This city also has numerous headquarters for many other universities. In addition, this metropolis has a large educational offer, focused on institutes, centers of technical formation and the universities already mentioned above.\n[[File:Campanil udec.jpg|thumb|180px|The campanile of the [[Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n]]]]\n[[File:San andres ucsc.JPG|thumb|180px|[[Universidad Cat\u00f3lica de la Sant\u00edsima Concepci\u00f3n]]]]\n[[File:Uss.jpg|thumb|180px|The [[Universidad San Sebasti\u00e1n]], Concepci\u00f3n headquarters, located at the [[Laguna Las Tres Pascualas]]]]\n[[File:Universidad Santo tomas concepcion.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Universidad Santo Tom\u00e1s (Chile)|Universidad Santo Tom\u00e1s]], Concepci\u00f3n headquarters, located in the Arturo Prat avenue]]\n\n===Universities===\nThe University Pencopolitana whose name was '''Pontificia Universidad Pencopolitana de La Concepci\u00f3n''' (Pontifical Pencopolitana University of The Conception) was an old university founded though a decree of the Bishop of Concepci\u00f3n, delivered to the administration of the [[Society of Jesus]] which functioned between the years 1724 and 1767. In May 24 of 1751 an [[1751 Concepci\u00f3n earthquake|earthquake]] followed by a [[tsunami]], ravaged the city causing serious damage, including the destruction of the library of the University and all of its funds. As a product of the fury of the waters, a rich collection of texts of the governance of southern Chile were lost, which resulted in a disaster for the culture and collective memory of the city. Due to the natural disasters, it was decided to relocate the city to the called [[Valle de la Mocha]], location where it is currently situated. Slowly the seminary was revived in the new location, in a period of decline in academic activity in Chilean monastic universities after the creation of the [[Universidad de San Felipe]], yet some degrees continued to be granted before the [[Suppression of the Society of Jesus]] in 1767.\nThe aforementioned University is considered to be the natural and legitimate predecessor of the [[Universidad Cat\u00f3lica de la Sant\u00edsima Concepci\u00f3n]] (UCSC), erected by the Archbishop of Concepci\u00f3n in 1991, from the [[Talcahuano]] Regional Headquarters of the [[Pontificia Universidad Cat\u00f3lica de Chile]].\n\nThe image of the Pontifical University of Concepci\u00f3n Pencopolitana, is still valid, for His Majesty [[Juan Carlos I of Spain|King Juan Carlos I of Spain]] in his 1990 speech on the occasion of his inauguration as Doctor Honoris Causa in the [[University of Chile]], in [[Santiago de Chile]], said: \"The work of the Pontifical University Pencopolitana should not be ignored, even before the creation of the University of San Felipe\" (Juan Carlos's account fails to acknowledge the existence of San Felipe's predecessor, the Dominican Universidad de Santo Tom\u00e1s de Aquino, from the sixteenth century in Santiago).\n\nMeanwhile, the University of Chile  allowed schools in the city to teach courses in law which allowed men to obtain a law degree. Among itsstudents was Henry Urrutia Manzano, who decades later became president of the Supreme Court of Chile.\n\nThe [[Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n]] was created in 1919 by a group of citizens including [[Enrique Molina Garmendia]], its first rector.\n\nEventually the university began to receive state support, becoming part of the [[Chilean Traditional Universities|traditional universities]], becoming one of three most important universities in the country, and the most importance at the regional level.\n\n====Traditional universities====\n* [[Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n]]\n* [[Universidad del B\u00edo-B\u00edo]]\n* [[Universidad Cat\u00f3lica de la Sant\u00edsima Concepci\u00f3n]]\n* [[Universidad T\u00e9cnica Federico Santa Mar\u00eda]]\n\n====Private universities====\n* [[Universidad del Desarrollo]]\n* [[Universidad Andr\u00e9s Bello]]\n* [[Universidad de Artes y Ciencias Sociales|Universidad Arcis]]\n* [[Universidad San Sebasti\u00e1n]]\n* [[Universidad Santo Tom\u00e1s (Chile)|Universidad Santo Tom\u00e1s]]\n* [[University of the Pacific (Chile)]]\n* [[Universidad de las Am\u00e9ricas (Chile)|Universidad de Las Am\u00e9ricas]]\n* [[Universidad Bolivariana]]\n* [[Universidad Pedro de Valdivia]]\n* [[Universidad La Rep\u00fablica]]\n* [[Universidad de Aconcagua]]\n* [[:es:Inacap|Universidad Tecnol\u00f3gica de Chile INACAP]]\n\n===Professional institutes===\n* [[Instituto Profesional DuocUC]], of the [[Pontificia Universidad Cat\u00f3lica de Chile]]\n* [[Instituto Profesional Virginio G\u00f3mez]], of the [[Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n]]\n* [[Instituto Tecnol\u00f3gico de la Universidad Cat\u00f3lica de la Sant\u00edsima Concepci\u00f3n|Instituto Tecnol\u00f3gico]], of the [[Universidad Cat\u00f3lica de la Sant\u00edsima Concepci\u00f3n]]\n* [[Instituto Profesional Santo Tom\u00e1s]], of the [[Universidad Santo Tom\u00e1s (Chile)|Universidad Santo Tom\u00e1s]]\n* [[Instituto Profesional AIEP]], of the [[Universidad Andr\u00e9s Bello]]\n* [[Instituto Profesional La Araucana]]\n* [[Instituto Profesional Providencia]]\n* [[Instituto de Estudios Bancarios Guillermo Subercaseaux]]\n* [[Instituto Profesional Diego Portales]]\n* [[Instituto Profesional Crecic]]\n* [[Instituto Profesional Placex]]\n* [[:es:Inacap|Instituto Profesional INACAP]]\n\n===Primary and secondary schools===\n{{expand section|date=April 2015}}\nThe city has a French international school, the ''[[Lyc\u00e9e Fran\u00e7ais Charles de Gaulle (Chile)|Lyc\u00e9e Fran\u00e7ais Charles de Gaulle]]'' and a German school, the Colegio Alem\u00e1n de Concepci\u00f3n and a British school, Saint John\u2019s School, the former located in the city downtown and the latter examples in San Pedro de la Paz. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dsc.cl/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-06-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180805104650/http://www.dsc.cl/ |archive-date=2018-08-05 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nThe city is served by [[Carriel Sur International Airport]] in Talcahuano.\n\n==Climate==\nThe climate of Concepci\u00f3n is classified as [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] ''Csb'', with a dry summer nadir in February. The cool waters of the Pacific Ocean help to maintain mild temperatures throughout the year. Temperatures rarely exceed {{convert|30|C|F}} or fall below {{convert|0|C|F|1}}. In the six-month period between May and October, the city receives approximately 83% of its total annual precipitation, which totals {{convert|1130|mm|in|abbr=on}}. The wettest month since records began in 1912 was June 2000 with {{convert|565.7|mm|in|1}}, whilst all months from November to April have been rainless on occasions.<ref>[https://archive.today/20120709074020/http://climexp.knmi.nl/data/tspa85682.txt Climate explorer for Concepci\u00f3n]</ref> The maritime cooling brings much cooler temperatures than nearby inland areas on the same parallel in [[Argentina]], where average summer highs match Concepci\u00f3n's all-time records. Summer temperatures for the [[36th parallel south|36 degrees latitude]] are rarely as cool as they are in Concepci\u00f3n, and on the Atlantic coast of Argentina, similar or hotter summer temperatures are found much further from the equator. However, this moderation is evident for the entire Chilean Pacific so is not unique for Concepci\u00f3n. Similar cool-summer [[mediterranean climate]] tendencies are found on the West Coast of North America on similar parallels, even though Concepci\u00f3n tends to have slightly wetter winters than [[San Francisco]] for example.\nConversely, record winter nighttime temperatures in Concepcion are significantly more moderate than temperatures recorded on the Argentine Atlantic coast at the same latitude, where temperatures below {{convert|-10|C|F}} have occurred.<ref>[https://www.smn.gob.ar/caracterizaci%C3%B3n-estad%C3%ADsticas-de-largo-plazo] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207103528/https://www.smn.gob.ar/caracterizaci%C3%B3n-estad%C3%ADsticas-de-largo-plazo |date=2019-02-07 }}{{Servicio Meteorologico Nacional|date=September 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location     = Concepci\u00f3n, Chile ([[Carriel Sur International Airport]]) 1981\u20132010, extremes 1966\u2013present\n|metric first = yes\n|single line  = yes\n|Jan record high C = 34.1\n|Feb record high C = 33.2\n|Mar record high C = 30.9\n|Apr record high C = 27.2\n|May record high C = 25.8\n|Jun record high C = 22.0\n|Jul record high C = 21.7\n|Aug record high C = 25.0\n|Sep record high C = 28.8\n|Oct record high C = 27.6\n|Nov record high C = 32.5\n|Dec record high C = 33.4\n|year record high C = 34.1\n|Jan high C = 22.8\n|Feb high C = 22.5\n|Mar high C = 21.0\n|Apr high C = 18.3\n|May high C = 15.4\n|Jun high C =